AS Nature is the Principle of Motion, o he is  alo of Ret and Sleep;
   Of Sleep, and how long it ought to be.
 which is the ceation of the actions of an Animal, to whom alone it hath been aigned, in regard no other Creature beides becomes weary in its Operations: For all Animals, even the lowet degree of Inects, leep; although uch who have hard eyes and cales, leep more obcurely then the ret; and Birds more lightly then four-footed Beats which uck, becaue they have a les and dryer Brain, and conequently les need leep, whoe ue is to moiten and refreh that part. Hence Man, having of all Animals the larget Brain, hath alo need of the longet leep, which ought to be about even hours. Wherefore I cannot but wonder that Plato, in his firt Book of Laws, would have his Citizens rie in the night to fall to their ordinary employments; for this diturbing of their ret were the way to make a Commonwealth of Fools; the Brain, by watchings acquiring a hot and dry intemperature, which begets igneous pirits, whoe mobility not permitting the Mind to conider the pecies impres'd upon them, is the caue of unteady and impetuous allies of the Mind; as, on the contrary, leep too exceive fills the ventricles of the Brain (wherein the Soul exercies her Faculties) with abundance of vapours and humidities, which offucating and troubling the pecies, the Mind thereby becomes lothful and dull.

Upon the Second Point it was aid, That God having ubjected  the Woman to the Dominion of the Man (endu'd with trength to keep himelf in poeion of that Empire;
                  Whether it is expedient for Women to be Learned?
               ) as Abolute Power is ometimes accompani'd with Tyranny, o he hath not only reerv'd to himelf alone the Authority of making Laws (whereunto Women not being call'd, have always had the wort) but hath alo appropriated the bet things to himelf, without, admitting them to partake therein: For Men, not content to have reduc'd them by thoe Laws into perpetual Wardhip, which is a real Servitude; to have o ill provided for them in Succeions; and to have made themelves Maters of their Etates, under the Title of Hubands; further, unjutly deprive them of the greatet of all Goods, to wit, that of the Mind, whoe fairet Ornament is Knowledge, the chief Good both of this World and the next, and the noblet Action of the Souls mot excellent Faculty, the Undertanding, which is common to Women as well as to Men, over whom too they eem to have the advantage of Wit; not only for the oftnes of their Fleh, which is an evidence of goodnes of Wit; but becaue of the Curioity, which is the Parent of Philoophy, defin'd, for this reaon, The Love and Deire of Wiedom: And this vivacity is conpicuous in their loquacity and their artifices, intrigues, and diimulations; their Wits being like thoe good Soils, which for want of better culture run out into weeds and briars. Their Memory, caus'd by the moit contitution of their Brain, and their edentary and olitary life, is further favourable to Study. Moreover, not to


peak of thoe of the preent Times, we have the examples of S. Bridgid, who excell'd in Mytical Theologie; Cleopatra, Siter of Arinous, in Phyick; Pulcheria, in Politicks; Hupetia and Athenais, wife to Theodoius, in Philoophy; Sappho, and two Corynnae, in Poetry; Cornelia, the Mother of the Gracchi, and Tullia, doubly Cicero's Daughter, in Eloquence. Now if it be true, that Politicks and Oeconomicks are founded upon the ame Principles, and there needs as much Knowledg to preerve as to acquire; then ince Women are in a Family what Men are in a State, and are detinated to keep what Men get, why hould not they have the knowledg of the ame Maxims as Men have by Study and Theory; inamuch as the reervednes and modety of their Sex allows them not to have the experience thereof, by frequentation of the World? Hence, our ancient Gauls left to them the Adminitration of the Laws, and other exercies of Peace; reerving to themelves only thoe of War. And as for other Sciences, ince their Encyclopaedy is a World which hath yet many unknown or les frequented Parts, if Women joyn'd together with Men in the dicovery of them, who doubts but a feminine Curioity would erve to exacuate the point of Mens Wits, ditracted by extraneous Affairs, and make marveilous progrees, and find out undry rare Secrets, hitherto unknown.

                Upon the Second Point it was aid, That the traight connexion between all the parts of the Univere makes this Quetion hard to be judg'd;
                  Whether it be better to Give than to Receive?
                ince they give nothing but what they receiv'd before. For our common Mother, the Earth, receives her fruitfulnes from the impreions of the Air; the Air, from the influence of the Stars; thee their light and power from the Sun; and he his from his Maker: Which the Platonists repreent to us by the mutual embraces of Porus and Penia; the one the God of Plenty, which is the original of Gifts; the other the Goddes of Neceity, which is the caue of Receiving; to hew, that they necearily follow one the other. And as in Nature the attenuated and rarifi'd Parts trongly attract the next for hindring vacuity, and the full reject what is uperfluous; o in Morality we may ay, That Giving and Receiving are equally good and natural, not differing but in certain terms and repects;


otherwie a Man might be aid more or les excellent or happy than himelf; there being no Peron but hath need to Receive and power to Give at the ame time, out of the Plenty or Neceity which he hath of omething; For hould he be tor'd with whatever he could wih, Might not we ask him, as S. Paul doth, What hat thou that thou hat not receiv'd? So then, 'tis Reception that hath put him into this happy tate; and if there be any excellence in Giving, it proceeds only from having Receiv'd before. Moreover, the three points which make a thing eteem'd in the World, Profit, Pleaure, and Honour, are all on the Receiver's ide: For he mut have renounc'd all the interets of Self-love that can believe there is more Profit and Pleaure in Giving than in Receiving. And as for Honour, although it eem more openly to favour the party of thoe that Give, nevertheles ince Giving and Receiving are Correlatives, the reaon of either mut be alike; and there cannot be Honour and Virtue in the one, but there mut be o in the other; nor, on the contrary, Blame and Ignominy in the Receiver, but it reflects back upon the Giver. And as he who loves, is les excellent than he who is lov'd, becaue he hath ome perfection in himelf which renders him lovely, which is ordinarily wanting in him who loves; o, between the Giver and the Receiver, the latter being as 'twere the Peron lov'd, may be aid more noble than he who Gives, who is the Lover; for there is no les Liberality in the one Peron to be willingly oblig'd, then in the other to oblige him; and beides, Virtue being a habit of the Will, he who Receives with Gratitude, and deires to Repay with Uury, may be aid as virtuous and as liberal in the act of his goodwill, as if he gave effectively. But this Virtue, commonly appropriated to the Giver, is oftentimes rather Otentation and Vanity, than true Virtue. For either the Man gives uch things as himelf needs, and then 'tis rather Folly than Virtue; or uch as are uperfluous, in which cae 'tis no Virtue for a Man to deprive himelf of a ueles thing. Yea, ometimes tis more ignominious and dihonet to Give than to Receive; for every thing retrain'd by the Laws is not only unjut, but vicious and dihonet: Now the mot part of Donations is retrain'd, not only by that rule of Givers, who ay, That the Title De Donationibus is the Title of Fools, becaue to Give is to Loe; but the Emperours had an expres Officer call'd Comes Sacrarum Largitionum, who was to retrench the uperfluity of their Gifts, and put in execution that Formula of our Chambers of Accompts, Trop donné oit repeté; Too large a Grant is to be recall'd. Yea, the Donations of private Perons were retrench'd by the ame Laws; even thoe between Husband and Wife; Legacies, by the Law Falcidia; Feoffments, by the Trebellian; Liberties, by the Caninian Law. But there can be no hame in receiving; ince not only Kings, but God himelf Receives from Men; and the Grandeur of the Meiah is not decrib'd by the Prophet, aving


by the Preents he was to receive of the Kings of Arabia and Saba; Gifts being a tetimony of their excellence to whom they are conferr'd: Whence the Lawyers hold, That a Tetamentary Legacy is a mark of Honour to the Legatee; as alo they call the Fee which Advocates receive, Honorarium: And the Wie-man commands us to Reward the Phyitian by the word of Honouring him. In fine, The praeeminence of Receiving above Giving ufficiently appears, in that our Lord invites us to Give, only by the promie and hope of Receiving an hundred fold.

The Second aid, That Poions and Antidotes, Medicaments and Aliments, are not call'd o abolutely, but as compar'd to the Natural Heat: For when ubdu'd and turn'd into the Animals Subtance, they are call'd Aliments; when Nature is alter'd by them, Medicaments; when detroy'd, Poions; when preerv'd from their malignity, Antidotes. Hence, according to the diverity of this heat, one ame thing is food to one and poion to others: As Hemlock is eaten by Goats and Quails, Henbane and Mandrakes by Swine, Cantharides by Swallows, Flies and Spiders by Poultry and Birds, although the ame be poion to Men; ome of whom do receive no hurt by poions, as 'tis reported of Mithridates, whoe body was o prepar'd by his Antidote compos'd of Rue, Nuts, and Figs, that he could not kill himelf by poion; of the Wench preented to Alexander who was fed with Napellus or Monks-hood; of the old Woman in Sextus Empiricus who wallow'd 30 drachms of Hemlock without harm; of Athenagoras the Argian who was not hurt by Scorpions, wherewith the Aethiopians dwelling neer the River


               Hydapes are fed as well as with Snakes, which Avicenna aith, another man kill'd by being bitten with them, poibly having his body full of a humour like fating pittle, which Galen aith kills Serpents and other Inects. Thee Poions and Antidotes are either Natural or Artificial; thoe more frequent in Southern then in Northern Countries, are communicated by Potions, Powders, Juices, Vapours, Touches, and other detetable means. The Natural differ either in Matter, or in Quantity, or in Quality, or in Operation. The Matter of Poyons, which is found almot every where, is either within us, as the Seed and the Blood, which by corruption oftentimes acquire a venomous quality; uch as alo is that of the matter of the Epilepie and Suffocation of the Womb: Or ele without us, in the Air, Water, and Earth; Fire alone being contrary to Poyon and putrefaction, which eaily happens to the Air and Water through their great humidity: But the Earth by its excrements and impurities upplies mot Matter to Poyons, which are drawn either from Minerals, from Plants, or from Animals. Arenic, Orpiment, Vitriol, Platre, Lime, Sublimate, Borax, Verdegreae, Quickilver, Cinabar, Cerue, and Red-lead, are of the firt order. To the econd belong Aconite or Woolf-bane, Chamalea or Widow-wayle, Yew, Spurge-lawrel, Thapia or corching Fennel, Tithymals, Hellebores, Vomiting Nut, Opium, Nighthade, and many other Plants; ome of which have only venomous Flowers, as certain white Violets; others only their Fruits, as the Apples of Mandrake; or only the juice, as Lettice and Poppies; or the Seeds, as Henbane and Spurge; or the Roots, as Aconite and Hellebore. To the third belong Lepus Marinus, the Salamander, the Flie call'd Bupretis, the Scorpion, Viper, Ap, Adder, Toad, Tarantula, Shrew-moue, and divers others; which are venomous either in all their parts, as Cantharides and Spiders; or only in ome, as Vipers in the Tail and Head, the Hart and Fork-fih in the extremities of their Tails, the Wivern in one of its Claws: Or in their Excrements; as the Gall of the Leopard, the Urine of a Moue, the Foam of a Mad-dog, the Sweat of an enraged Hore, and the Blood of a Bull. As for the Quantity; although all Poyons act in a little volume, yet ome require les Matter; as Opium acts in les quantity than Hemlock; this, than the juice of Leeks; and this, than the juice of Lettice. According to Quality; ome are hot, and either inflame, as Euphorbium; or corrode, as the Lepus Marinus, which particularly invades the Lungs; the Ap, the Liver; Nighthade and Henbane, the Brain; Cantharides, the Bladder. Others are cold, fixing the Spirits and natural heat, or hindring their free motion; as Opium, and the Salt of Lead. Others are dry; as Lime, Vitriol, and Arenic, which conume the Radical Humidity: For Humidity being a quality purely paive, and of it elf incapable of cauing pain, there are no Poyons imply humid. They differ alo in their manner of acting;


the cold kill by conopiting or tifling the Heat; Hellebore by vehement attraction of the Humours: Some corrode the Subtance; others alter, reolve, or putrifie it. And becaue all Poions chiefly attaque the natural Heat, and the Heart; as the Swoonings, Palpitations, and Weaknees accompanying them witnes: The Antidotes mut be Cardiacal or friends to the Heart, trengthening it, and joyning forces with it to expel or ubdue the malignity of the Poyon.

Upon the Second Point it was aid, That the Eye and the Ear  being the Senes whereby the Mind receives the Species of things which it knows; the former is proper for Invention;
                  Whether the Reading of Books is a fitter way for Learning than Vocal Intruction?
                and the latter, call'd the Sene of Dicipline, chiefly for Learning. For the Voice, as the Proverb aith, is more powerful than dumb Maters; becaue being animated with the geture and motion of the Eyes, Mouth, Hands, and whole Body, it makes more impreion upon the Mind than the dead tyle of Books; which beides, being Intructors whom we cannot interrogate concerning our doubts, as we may the living, they leave more cruples in the Readers mind than they reolve: For our cognition depending on the Species and Animal Spirits, thee follow the drift and motion of the Voice, whoe accents conequently being joyful, ad, amorous, warlike, or furious, according to the variety of the ubject, imprint like affections in the Soul; and this through the near communication there is between the Air and thoe Spirits of the Body, which are alo aerious, and of great mobility. And ince Writing is only the ign of Speech, as this is of the Minds conception, it les perfectly exprees its Author's thought than the Voice, the perfect Image of his Conception, which is call'd the Internal Speech, as the voice is the External; and being the Original from which Writing is drawn, repreents our Conceptions better than the Copy; as all Exemplars degenerat proportionably to their remotenes from their Prototype.

The Fourth aid, That all the Language of Adam, who gave names uitable to the nature of every thing being lot except the the name of God (for that reaon o much eteemed by the Jews); The Cabalits in imitation of that Tongue, invented one whereof I hall give you a tate. It hath five Vowels E, A, , I, O, which anwer to the Elements and the Heaven; E, to Earth; A, to the Water; 
                  , to the Air; I, to the Fire; and O, to Heaven. E, produceth in pronunciation c, d, f, g, l, m, n, p, r, , t, z; foramuch as thee Cononants cannot be produc'd without it; A, produceth h, and k; v, produceth q; I, produceth nothing, becaue pure and ingle Fire doth not. O, likewie produceth nothing, becaue the Heaven only moves and excites Generations: whereas E produceth abundance of Letters, reembling the Earth which produceth every thing in its boom,


being the Centre of Heaven and the Matrix of the Elements. Now, to form words according to the Elementary Qualities, they will have the Vowels which compoe uch a word anwer to the Elements which compoe uch a mixt body. And to pecifie degrees, becaue the Vowels, whereby they are denoted meeting together would poil the pronunciation, therefore they make foure orders of the ixteen Cononants, viz. b, c, d, f, denote the four degrees of Fire; g, l, m, n, thoe of Air; p, r, , t, thoe of Water; x, z, , t, thoe of Earth. Upon this foundation they build the compoition of all their Words, which they compoe of Vowels according to the Elements predominant in things, and of Cononants according to their degree. But who ees not the aburdity of this invention, which by this means would extend only to corporeal mixts, whereof the quality and very degree is known: Concerning which Naturalits are o far from being agreed, that many attribute mot natural effects to other caues, as to Occult Properties, o call'd in oppoition to the Elementary. 'Tis bet therefore not to rove from the common tract which teaches us the Sciences by real Languages; amongt which thoe call'd Dead ones, to wit, the Hebrew, Greek, and Latine, and others now dius'd, uffice not for teaching the Sciences, becaue they are not pronounc'd well, and the learned agree not about the importance of many Letters and Syllables. Beides, the mot eloquent expres not themelves o naturally in thoe antick obolete Tongues as in their own. And all confes that in order to obtain the perfection of a Science, too much plainnes cannot be us'd, either on the Teacher's part in etablihing their Rules and Precepts, or on the Learner's in propounding their difficulties for reolution.

The Sixth aid, That high Myteries have alwayes been veil'd under contemptible, and oftentimes ridiculous Figures; as if the widom of the ublimer Spirits meant to mock thoe of the vulgar, who judge of things only by appearance. Which may have place in common effects; but as for extraordinary things, their caues are o too, whereof we have experiences in Nature ufficiently manifet. There is no affinity between a word and the death it gives to a Serpent; yet the Poet attets the thing in this Vere,
Frigidus in pratis cantando rumpitur Anguis;
between the ight of a little bird call'd a Wit-wall, and the Jaundies, which it cures; between the Figure call'd Abacus Lunae, and the Meagrim, which is alo cur'd thereby; between a point ty'd, and the Generative Power which it hinders. In brief, the mot excellent effects are of this kind, and deerve not the name of admirable, unles when our mind finds no connexion between the effect and the caue that produceth it. Why then may not the ame reality be admitted between this Character and the effects pretended by thoe Brothers of the Roie-Cros?

The econd aid, that it was as dangerous for us to involve in impoibilities whatever we have not een, as to be over-credulous in believing all. But when Reaon and Authority, which bring experience with them, and aure us of a thing, appear of any ide, our credulity may well be excus'd. And this is the cae, in the quetion concerning Satyrs, inamuch as the concurrence of the eeds of thoe two pecies, whereof they conit, may as well produce them, as the Mule is engendred of an As and a Mare. Whereto may be added this, as a general acknowledgment, that Nature hath not omitted any thing of that which might compleat her power, as having produc'd from Nothing, even to the mot excellent Beings, whatever was to come into the mean between both. Beides, though the Imaginations of Mothers were not capable of all things, and cannot imprint that figure and change of body on the Infant, nay to make what they pleas'd of it, whereof there are daily intances, that ometimes they do; yet the commonage of fields and forrets, and uch nourihment as the Children might have taken from Goats, as well as Romulus and Remus did it from a She-Wolf, might, in proces of time, incline them to uch or uch a form. Whereto it will ignifie little to oppoe the reaon of Lucretius, ince it eems erroneous, by what is commonly done in the ordering of Trees, which are promicuouly engrafted in different kinds, as for example, an Apple-tree may be in a Cabbadge-taulk. By which intermixture, the Apples growing on uch a Tree, hall not only have a little cent of the Cabbadge, but alo, that which is wore always prevailing over that which is better, whereas the Apple-tree hould lat many years, and the Cabbadg is but of one, from thee two extremities there aries a mean, to wit, a Tree which lives longer then a Cabbadge, and not o long as an Apple-tree hould: Which thing is alo to be oberv'd ingraffing upon different kinds of Tree. Thence it comes that S. Hierom, in the life of St. Paul the Hermit, peaking of the Centaur that appear'd to S. Anthony (for it is true, that the ubitance of one of thee Monters proves that of the other; as the one being detroy'd, the other cannot ubit) does not affirm it to be a pure illuion, but doubts whether it were a real Centaur, uch as thoe poken of among the Ancients, or a Devil that had aum'd that form. But S. Anthony, took him for a Man, and not for a Devil whom he knew to be a Lyar, ince he ask'd him where the Servant of God, whom he ought for, lodged. Whereto the Centaur reply'd but in a avage voice, and uch as could not be undertood, whereupon he drew near to S. Anthony, and with his hand hew'd him the way he hould go, which done he ran away. Whence Saint Hierom concludes, that it is a hard matter to know, Whether the Devil had not appear'd under that Figure to frighten that holy peron;


or that the Deart, fruitful in Monters, had produc'd that Beat. And Plato, in the Banquet of the Wie-men relates, that a certain Shepherd having preented Periander with a Child, brought forth at his houe by a Mare, having the Head, Neck, and Hands like thoe of a Man, in all the other parts reembling a Hore, and having the voice of a Child; Diocles propos'd, that uch Prodigies were the fore-runners of Seditions, and Ditraction of mens minds. Whereto Thales reply'd, that it was a natural thing, to prevent which for the future, he advis'd him to keep no Grooms but uch as were married. 'Tis alo the advice of Pliny, who in the eventh Book of his Natural History, affirms, that in the Country of the Cartadulones, among the Mountains of the Indies, there are Satyrs, a ort of very wift Animals, running ometimes on two feet, ometimes on all four, having a humane hape, and uch as by reaon of their activity are never taken, till they are old or ick. Plutarch alo affirms, in the Life of Sylla, that in his return from Italy, there was brought him a Satyr, like thoe decrib'd by the Ancient Authors, half-man, and half-goat, which had been taken leeping. Being ak'd who he was, his Anwer was in uch a Dialect as favour'd nothing of Man's Language, but in an articulate voice, between that of Goats, and the neighing of Hores; and the reult was, that Sylla taking compaion of him, ent a Guard to conduct him to the place from whence he had been brought. The ame Author makes mention of the death of the God Pan, who was a Satyr. Saint Hierom in the place before cited, affirms, that another Satyr poke; and he gives a decription of him, aying, that he was of a middle tature, having a crooked Noe, hornes on his fore-head, and feet like thoe of a Goat; and that he brought Saint Paul the Hermit ome Dates, not taken off the bough on which they had grown: Which kindnes obliges the Saint to ak him, Who he was? Whereto he made Anwer, that he was a mortal, and one of the Inhabitants of that Hermitage, whom the abus'd Pagans adored for Fawnes, Satyrs, and Incubi. I come to you, continu'd he, as a Deputy from the ret of our Company, intreating you to pray for us to your God and ours, whom we acknowledge to be come into the world for the common alvation of all. Having with thoe words concluded his Embaie, the light-footed Animal ran away. And that this Relation may eem the les trange, we have this further to add, that in the time of Contantine, there was one of them brought alive to Alexandria, which was expos'd before the people at the publick Shews, and afterwards dying, his Body was alted, and tranported to the City of Antioch to be hewn to the Emperour. Pauanias alo relates, that he had heard it of one Euphemius, who, he ayes, was a peron worthy of credit, that ailing into Spain, he was hurry'd by a Tempet to certain Ilands full of a avage kind of men, who had their bodies all over hairy, long tails like thoe of Hores, and red


hair, which they could not force away from about them, otherwie then with blows; and that one of the Women-avages having been left upon the hore by the Mariners, thoe Savages abus'd her with all imaginable violences. So that, to doubt whether there be any Satyrs, after o many Tetimonies that there are, were to have too great a complyance for our own Senes, and too little for the Tetimonies of the Ancients.
